<font color="#FF0000">TQM AND THE VETERAN</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 20  0:43:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This is the direction, and what both veterans and non-veterans need to hear.  We have gained a unique perspective, and a unique vision of what can be.  Sometimes I think that I see things so much differently because many in corporate life have built their organization's structure based upon management philosophies which date back to WWII.  <br><br>
When I flew in the USAF, I was given the authority to make decisions on the lives of survivors.  At one point I called in an Army Chinook to air evac an injured soldier who had driven off a cliff in a jeep (non-combat, but he still was hurting).  I went out in an ambulance from 1st Med Battalion, 1st Marine Division's Field Hospital in Danang, and came back by helicopter, which startled the hospital personnel.  <br><br>
That kind of authority to make things happen, which we had over there, is still rare in the business world.  But this was what Demming and others talk about with quality management.  This is some of the contributions I think that the veterans have that are not being used enough today.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


